The most provincial thing about Americans is how for some reason they feel a compulsion to constantly talk about "what it means to be an American", it reminds you of small rural schools in Eastern Europe talking about "our values" on ceremonies that students are forced to attend.

Imagine if Austrians forced themselves to talk about how being Austrian meant "being a rebel" and not following rules or sticking to simple folkish religious wisdom. Better to just be an honest globalist than force yourself to parody patriotism even under layers of self-awareness
There's one author called Yovkov whose short stories are better than anything else I've read but he's mostly untranslated, I don't think we have a truly good novel

Really life is mostly the same anywhere. Both the USA and Afghanistan call themselves "home of the brave". Being too preoccupied with what it means to be from the village of Dygulybgey instead of the village of Yekaterinogradskaya distracts from more important questions.

All "patriotism" through history from FDR through Churchill to Stalin has hardly been distinguishable from Andrew Tate driving his rented car around Romanian highways and pointing out: "you see this, this is a church, this means tradition, the bell here rings every single day..."

The "First Russian National Army" fought what was considered "Russia" at the time, because they knew they were it; if you are yourself to yourself, then anything presented to you as you is a changeling, a doppelganger, a False Dimitry pretender posing to usurp your yourself-ness.
I don't think they would be enjoyable that way at all to be fully honest
